In C++ programming, the `if-else if` structure is used when you have multiple conditions to evaluate and want to execute only one block of code that matches the first true condition.

This structure helps control program flow efficiently when several mutually exclusive conditions exist.

**Syntax**
```cpp
if (condition1) {
    // Executes if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // Executes if condition2 is true
} else {
    // Executes if none of the above conditions are true
}
```
---

**Example**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Declare and initialize marks
    int marks = 78;

    // Check if marks are greater than or equal to 75
    if (marks >= 75) {
        cout = 40) {
        cout << "Grade: Between D and B" << endl;  // Average performance
    }
    // If marks are below 40
    else {
        cout << "Grade: F" << endl;  // Failing grade
    }

    return 0;
}
```
**Expected Output**
```default
Grade: B or higher
```

